                        Return 0
                    End If

                    Let fn_p_exit be proc invoke_child_exit with context, node, node_type, i
                    If fn_p_exit is equal to 0:
                        Return 0
                    End If
                End If

                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Note: Visit return type (offset 32) at child_index = param_count
        Let return_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
        If return_type is not equal to 0:
            Let fn_rt_enter be proc invoke_child_enter with context, node, node_type, param_count
            If fn_rt_enter is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Set result to proc visit_hir_node with context, return_type
            If result is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Let fn_rt_exit be proc invoke_child_exit with context, node, node_type, param_count
            If fn_rt_exit is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
        End If

        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Primitive and unknown types have no children
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "visit_pattern_children" takes context as Integer, node as Integer, node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Visit children of HIR pattern nodes (14000-14999)

    @Reasoning:
    Pattern nodes encode the structural matchers used by match expressions
    and destructuring lets: identifier bindings, literal matches, wildcards,
    tuple/record/variant/array destructuring, range matchers, type-checked
    patterns, guard patterns, or-patterns, and rest patterns. HIRPattern
    uses a uniform 48-byte layout (pattern_type, matched_type, bindings,
    binding_count, subpatterns, subpattern_count), so the only HIR child
    nodes a pattern can carry are its subpatterns - bindings are symbol
    pointers (semantic objects, not HIR nodes) and matched_type is a
    HIRTypeInfo pointer reached through the type-traversal axis, not as
    a pattern child. The visitor walks subpatterns in stable source order
    (the order add_pattern_subpattern recorded them), giving each child a
    contiguous child_index starting at 0. Every recursive visit_hir_node
    call is wrapped in the per-child triple (invoke_child_enter,
    visit_hir_node, invoke_child_exit). Null subpattern slots are skipped
    entirely - their child_index is not surfaced to the per-child hooks.
    Leaf patterns (identifier, literal, wildcard, rest) carry no
    subpatterns and fall through to a no-op return.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
    HIRPattern structure (from hir_nodes.runa::create_hir_pattern):
    - offset 0: pattern_type (constant in 14000-14999 range)
    - offset 8: matched_type (HIRTypeInfo pointer; visited via type axis)
    - offset 16: bindings (List of HIR symbol pointers; not HIR children)
    - offset 24: binding_count
    - offset 32: subpatterns (List of HIR pattern child pointers)
    - offset 40: subpattern_count

    Every pattern constant 14000-14011 (HIR_IDENTIFIER_PATTERN,
    HIR_LITERAL_PATTERN, HIR_TUPLE_PATTERN, HIR_RECORD_PATTERN,
    HIR_WILDCARD_PATTERN, HIR_TYPE_PATTERN, HIR_GUARD_PATTERN,
    HIR_RANGE_PATTERN, HIR_VARIANT_PATTERN, HIR_ARRAY_PATTERN,
    HIR_OR_PATTERN, HIR_REST_PATTERN) uses the same 48-byte layout.
    Dispatch is therefore unified: read subpatterns at offset 32 and
    subpattern_count at offset 40, iterate i in 0..subpattern_count, and
    for each non-null child invoke child_enter(i), recurse via
    visit_hir_node, then invoke child_exit(i). Stop-flag propagation is
    handled by the invoke_child_enter / invoke_child_exit return values
    per the v0.75 child-hook protocol.

    child_index semantics per pattern kind (all using stable subpattern
    order, contiguous from 0):
    - HIR_IDENTIFIER_PATTERN (14000): leaf; no subpatterns.
    - HIR_LITERAL_PATTERN    (14001): leaf; no subpatterns.
    - HIR_TUPLE_PATTERN      (14002): element i = child_index i.
    - HIR_RECORD_PATTERN     (14003): field-pattern i = child_index i.
    - HIR_WILDCARD_PATTERN   (14004): leaf; no subpatterns.
    - HIR_TYPE_PATTERN       (14005): inner pattern = child_index 0.
    - HIR_GUARD_PATTERN      (14006): underlying pattern = child_index 0,
      guard condition pattern (if encoded as subpattern) = child_index 1.
    - HIR_RANGE_PATTERN      (14007): lower bound = 0, upper bound = 1
      (when bounds are encoded as literal sub-patterns).
    - HIR_VARIANT_PATTERN    (14008): payload pattern i = child_index i.
    - HIR_ARRAY_PATTERN      (14009): element-or-rest pattern i = child_index i.
    - HIR_OR_PATTERN         (14010): alternative pattern i = child_index i.
    - HIR_REST_PATTERN       (14011): leaf; no subpatterns.

    Because all pattern kinds share a single subpattern list and the
    list is the only HIR-child carrier, a single uniform loop covers
    every case while still honoring the per-pattern child_index
    semantics documented above. Pattern kinds that have no subpatterns
    naturally execute zero iterations.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
    Two memory reads (offsets 32 and 40) followed by a linear walk over
    subpattern_count children. No allocation, no branching on pattern
    kind, no recursion overhead beyond the per-child triple required by
    the visitor protocol. Leaf patterns (identifier, literal, wildcard,
    rest) complete in two reads plus an immediate Return 1, matching
    the cost profile of leaf expression nodes in visit_expression_children.
    Composite patterns iterate exactly subpattern_count times with no
    skipped slots in steady state - the null-child guard exists only to
    defend against partially constructed nodes during HIR-build error
    recovery.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
    Null-node guard short-circuits before any field read. The
    subpattern_count read is bounded by the pattern's own count field,
    so a corrupt or truncated subpattern list pointer cannot trigger
    an over-read - the worst case is a missed child, flagged by
    validate_hir_tree downstream. Null subpattern entries are skipped
    rather than dereferenced. Pattern kinds outside the recognised
    14000-14011 range still execute the same uniform walk (offsets 32
    and 40 are reserved for subpatterns / subpattern_count by the
    HIRPattern layout contract), so future pattern constants slotted
    into 14012-14999 inherit correct child traversal automatically.
    @End Security_Scope

    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: All HIR pattern kinds share the uniform 48-byte HIRPattern layout.
    Note: Subpatterns list is at offset 32, count is at offset 40.
    Let subpatterns be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    Let subpattern_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 40

    If subpatterns is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    If subpattern_count is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than subpattern_count:
        Let subpattern be proc get from List with subpatterns, i

        If subpattern is not equal to 0:
            Let sub_enter be proc invoke_child_enter with context, node, node_type, i
            If sub_enter is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Let sub_result be proc visit_hir_node with context, subpattern
            If sub_result is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Let sub_exit be proc invoke_child_exit with context, node, node_type, i
            If sub_exit is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Specialized Visitor Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "count_nodes" takes root as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Count total number of nodes in HIR tree

    @Reasoning:
    Utility function to count all nodes in HIR tree by visiting
    every node and incrementing counter. Used by HIR statistics
    output, MIR/LIR pre-allocation heuristics, and the test harness
    to verify visitor coverage. Reuses the standard visitor pipeline
    rather than implementing an ad-hoc traversal so it inherits
    cycle detection and stable per-child order automatically.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
    1. Allocate an 8-byte counter cell initialised to 0; this lives
       outside the visitor context because we want to read it after
       the context is destroyed.
    2. Create a visitor context with no pre/post or per-child hooks
       (we count by walking, not by callback) and the counter as
       user_data so a custom counting callback (or future plug-in)
       can find it.
    3. Drive a full traversal via visit_hir_tree; cycle detection
       prevents double-counting in HIR graphs with shared subtrees.
    4. Read the final count, destroy the visitor context, free the
       counter cell, and return the count.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
    Two allocations (counter + visitor) - constant cost. Traversal
    cost is linear in the number of HIR nodes. Cycle detection adds
    an O(depth) factor on every push but is unavoidable for HIR
    graphs.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
    Failure paths release the counter allocation before returning
    so no allocation leaks on OOM. Counter overflow is bounded by
    the 64-bit address space - no real HIR tree can exceed it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If root is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create counter (allocate Integer)
    Let counter be proc allocate from Layout with 8

    If counter is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with counter, 0, 0  Note: Initialize to 0

    Note: Create visitor context (no callbacks needed, just traverse)
    Let context be proc create_visitor_context with 0, 0, counter, 0, 0

    If context is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with counter
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Count nodes by traversing tree
    proc visit_hir_tree with root, context

    Note: Get final count
    Let final_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with counter, 0

    Note: Cleanup
    proc destroy_visitor_context with context
    proc deallocate from Layout with counter

    Return final_count
End Process

Process called "find_node_by_type" takes root as Integer, target_type as Integer, callback as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Find first node of specified type in HIR tree using caller-provided callback

    @Reasoning:
    Utility function to search for the first node matching target_type.
    The caller supplies the comparison/storage callback so the visitor
    itself remains agnostic about how a match is defined - downstream
    consumers can search by type, by symbol id, by source location,
    or by any computed predicate. Early termination via the visitor
    stop flag keeps the search cost bounded by the position of the
    first match, not by total tree size.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
    Callback signature: callback(node, node_type, user_data, context) -> Integer
    - user_data points to a 16-byte block:
        offset 0: target_type
        offset 8: result_ptr (initialised to 0)
    - Callback responsibilities:
      1. Compare node_type to target_type at user_data offset 0.
      2. On match: store node at user_data offset 8 and return 0
         to set the stop flag and terminate the traversal.
      3. On miss: return 1 to continue.
    1. Reject null root and null callback - the callback is mandatory.
    2. Allocate a 16-byte search context and initialise both fields.
    3. Create a visitor with the callback as pre-visit (matches are
       discoverable in pre-order so deeper instances of the same type
       are not consulted) and no post or per-child hooks.
    4. Drive the traversal; the callback writes any match into the
       search context.
    5. Read the result pointer, destroy the visitor and the search
       context, and return the found node (0 if no match).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
    Best case O(1) - root matches and stop flag fires immediately.
    Worst case O(N) - target_type does not appear and the full tree
    is walked. The stop-flag short-circuit guarantees no work is
    done after the first match, including no allocation in the
    callback path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
    The callback pointer is invoked at every node; the caller is
    responsible for the callback's body safety. All allocations
    (search context, visitor context) are released on every exit
    path - including OOM and null-callback rejection. Result pointer
    of 0 unambiguously signals no match, distinguishing it from a
    successful match storing a non-null node pointer.
    @End Security_Scope

    If root is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If callback is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Callback is required for search
    End If

    Note: Create user_data structure: [target_type, result_ptr]
    Let user_data be proc allocate from Layout with 16

    If user_data is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize user_data fields
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with user_data, 0, target_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with user_data, 8, 0  Note: result_ptr starts null

    Note: Create visitor context with callback
    Let context be proc create_visitor_context with callback, 0, user_data, 0, 0

    If context is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with user_data
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Visit tree - callback will check types and store result
    proc visit_hir_tree with root, context

    Note: Get found node from user_data
    Let found_node be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with user_data, 8

    Note: Cleanup
    proc destroy_visitor_context with context
    proc deallocate from Layout with user_data

    Return found_node
End Process

Process called "validate_hir_tree" takes root as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate HIR tree structure and detect cycles

    @Reasoning:
    Utility function to validate HIR tree by traversing and checking
    for structural issues (cycles, null pointers in required fields).
    Uses the visitor's built-in cycle detection counter rather than a
    custom walker so the validation contract is identical to the
    contract every other consumer (analysis, transformation, codegen)
    sees during normal traversal - if validate_hir_tree passes, every
    other visitor pass is guaranteed cycle-free.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
    1. Reject null root - it cannot represent a valid HIR program.
    2. Create a visitor context with all callback slots null - we
       only need the framework's built-in cycle detection and
       null-child accounting.
    3. Drive a full traversal via visit_hir_tree. During the walk,
       visitor_push_node increments error_count (offset 48) every
       time a node appears twice in the active stack.
    4. Read error_count after the walk completes.
    5. Destroy the visitor context.
    6. Return 1 when error_count is 0, else 0 to signal a structural
       defect.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
    Equivalent to a full empty-callback traversal: O(N * depth) due
    to push-time cycle scan. Memory cost is the visitor context plus
    the visit stack, both released on exit.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
    Validation produces a single boolean result without exposing
    internal pointers or error details, so it is safe to expose to
    untrusted callers. A failure indicates the HIR is unsafe to
    feed into downstream passes; the caller must NOT proceed with
    optimisation or code generation on a tree that returned 0.
    @End Security_Scope

    If root is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Null root is invalid
    End If

    Note: Create visitor context
    Let context be proc create_visitor_context with 0, 0, 0, 0, 0

    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Visit tree - cycle detection happens automatically
    proc visit_hir_tree with root, context

    Note: Check if any errors were detected
    Let error_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 48

    Note: Cleanup
    proc destroy_visitor_context with context

    Note: Valid if no errors detected
    If error_count is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: End of HIR Visitor implementation
